Indication: Evaluate for potential osteomyelitis.

Covid test date: heart failure.

Service date: June 21, 2020. Diabetes.

Patient is a 20-year-old female.

The stable pelvic nodule measured 3.1 x 2.2 x 3.3 cm, previously 3 cm.

Two severe cysts measured 3.1 cm x 2.2 cm and 11 mm.

A mild to moderate lesion around the stomach measures 2-3 cm.

Tumor is up to 3 cm.

Tumor is larger than 3 cm.

Tumor is up to 2 cm x 3 cm.

He had neck pain from August 1 to August 14.

Advanced liver cancer with metastasis.

Ectopic pregnancy.

Incomplete spontaneous abortion on June 5 at 3 pm.

These findings were communicated to Dr. Jones on September 5 at 4 pm.

The findings were sent to JANE DOE.

On January 5, The findings were discussed with Dr. Smith at 3 pm.

A follow-up scan of the injury of the right foot within 2 weeks is recommended.

An x-ray of the fracture of the right arm in January 2022 is advised.

I recommend a follow-up of the cancer.

Findings: The left foot looks normal.

An enlarged elbow wound.

There is approximately 50% stenosis of the post bulbar left ICA.

Acute sepsis.

Birads 2.

A changing tumor.

Both the FDA and Society of Breast Imaging/American College of Radiology recommend mammography as the most effective screening method for detecting breast cancer in its early, most treatable stages.
